      "remediation": {
        "topic": "API versioning",
        "mini_lesson": "Think of your favorite restaurant's menu as an API, detailing what dishes (data/functions) you can order. Just like a chef might evolve a popular recipe\u2014perhaps changing ingredients or preparation methods\u2014API developers often modify their services over time. API versioning is like the restaurant offering 'Menu v1.0' and introducing a 'Menu v2.0' when significant changes occur. This ensures that customers (client applications) who learned to order from v1.0 don't suddenly receive a different dish than expected, preventing 'broken' experiences. It allows older clients to continue functioning with the previous recipe while new clients can use the updated version, providing a smooth transition and predictable service for everyone.",
        "follow_up_question": "If a food delivery app was built to order a specific sandwich from 'Restaurant API v1.0' and the restaurant then made a significant change to that sandwich's ingredients without releasing a 'v2.0' API, what potential problem would the delivery app and its users face?",
        "user_answer": "APIs use versioning so old clients keep working while new ones adopt the new contract.",
        "status": "completed",
        "attempts": 1
      }
    },
